"description": "The Self-Implicative Method designates the artistic-epistemological practice through which the artist critically intervenes in the contemporary regimes of existence of their own work, recognizing that documentation, cataloguing, circulation, ontologies, metadata, and algorithmic systems no longer merely describe the artwork, but actively participate in its historicity, recoverability, and public intelligibility. This critical reinscription does not seek to control meaning; it constitutes a continuation of artistic practice and a form of thought production."      "skos:definition": {
        "@value": "The Self-Implicative Method designates an artistic-epistemological practice situated within the post-conceptual condition, through which the artist deliberately intervenes in the regimes of existence of their own work. It does not seek to control the meaning of the artwork, but to intervene critically in the documentary, semantic, and computational conditions through which it continues to exist, circulate, be recovered, and produce thought.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "skos:scopeNote": {
        "@value": "Applies to practices in which artistic production is prolonged through conscious interventions in the systems responsible for the documentation, circulation, recoverability, and intelligibility of artworks. It is not equivalent to autobiography, memoir, artist testimony, artist statement, autoethnography, or the defense of authorial intention. It also does not replace external criticism.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "skos:historyNote": {
        "@value": "The concept is progressively formulated in Alexandre Mury's own corpus. Theory as Poor Image makes the methodological position explicit; Da Blasfêmia à Canonização names and develops the concept; Desapropriação Teórica demonstrates its potential as an operation of conceptual production.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
